+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| 25th Anniversary of the Sinclair ZX Spectrum                       |
|   from the never-even-seen-one dept.                               |
|   posted by CmdrTaco on Monday April 23, @08:43 (Emulation (Games))|
|   http://games.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/23/1214256        |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Alioth writes "Twenty five years ago today, Sinclair Research launched
[1]Britain's most popular home computer of the 1980s — the Sinclair ZX
Spectrum. Costing about one third of the price of its rivals such as the
Commodore 64 while having a faster CPU and a better BASIC interpreter,
the machine sold well in many guises throughout the 1980s and had more
than a staggering 9,000 software titles. The machine may well have done
well in the US too, had Timex — the company building the machine under
license in the US — not already been in financial trouble and about to
fold. The machine was also extremely successful in Russia, although not
for Sinclair Research — because the Russians made dozens of different
clones of the machine, and did so right into the mid 1990s. The machine
still has a [0]healthy retro scene, including the development of new
commercial software by [2]Cronosoft, and new hardware such as the
[3]DivIDE, which allows a standard PC hard disc or compact flash card to
be connected to the machine."

Discuss this story at:
    http://games.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/23/1214256

Links:
    0. http://www.worldofspectrum.org/
    1. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sinclair_Spectrum
    2. http://cronosoft.white.prohosting.com/cronosoft/
    3. http://baze.au.com/divide/


