+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| New Theory Links Biodiversity to the Stars                         |
|   from the long-wait-for-results-returned dept.                    |
|   posted by ScuttleMonkey on Monday April 23, @16:00 (Space)       |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/04/23/1735226      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]eldavojohn writes "Space.com's Mystery Monday has an article proposing
a hypothesis that our solar system's undulations [1]directly affects
biodiversity on earth through cosmic-ray exposure. There's data that,
through the fossil record, shows us earth's biodiversity [2]peaking again
and again until a great cataclysmic period where it is greatly reduced.
The theory essentially suggests that this 62 million year cycle can be
attributed to how our solar system moves within the milky way galaxy
which turns out to be a 64 million year cycle. It's a plausible
explanation though very tough to prove, hopefully we don't have to wait
around 64 million years to draw a conclusion on this hypothesis."

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/04/23/1735226

Links:
    0. mailto:djohnsop@gmu.edu
    1. http://www.space.com/scienceastronomy/070423_cosmic_evo.html
    2. http://www.space.com/php/multimedia/imagedisplay/img_display.php?pic=070423_bio_cycle_02.jpg&cap=The+62+million+year+fossil+diversity+cycle+is+most+evident+in+the+historical+records+of+genera+that+survived+less+than+45+million+years.+A+genera+is+a+group+of+similar+species.+Curiously%2C+some+organisms+seem+immune+to+the+cycle.+Corals%2C+sponges+and+trilobites+follow+the+cycle%2C+while+fish%2C+squid+and+snails+do+not.+Credit%3A+Robert+Rohde+and+Richard+Muller%2C+U.C.+Berkeley


